  "prompt": "What are the best anime movies?",
  "response": "There are many exceptional anime movies that have captivated audiences worldwide. Here are some of the best and most influential ones, spanning different genres and styles:\n\n1. **Spirited Away (2001)** - Directed by Hayao Miyazaki, this Studio Ghibli film won an Academy Award for Best Animated Feature and is a beautifully animated tale about a young girl navigating a spirit world.\n\n2. **My Neighbor Totoro (1988)** - Another classic from Hayao Miyazaki, this film tells the story of two young girls who encounter friendly forest spirits in rural Japan.\n\n3. **Your Name (Kimi no Na wa) (2016)** - Directed by Makoto Shinkai, this romantic fantasy involves two teenagers who discover they can swap bodies and the mysterious connection between their lives.\n\n4. **Akira (1988)** - A groundbreaking cyberpunk film directed by Katsuhiro Otomo, \"Akira\" is known for its stunning animation and complex themes surrounding power and technology.\n\n5. **Princess Mononoke (1997)** - A darker adventure from Miyazaki, this film explores the conflict between nature and industrialization through the story of a young warrior who gets involved in the struggle for the forest.\n\n6. **Grave of the Fireflies (1988)** - Directed by Isao Takahata, this heartbreaking film tells the story of two siblings struggling to survive in Japan during World War II.\n\n7. **The Wind Rises (2013)** - Another Miyazaki masterpiece, this film is a semi-biographical story about Jiro Horikoshi, the designer of the Mitsubishi A6M Zero fighter plane.\n\n8. **Howl's Moving Castle (2004)** - A fantastical tale of love and war, this film features stunning visuals and a strong anti-war message.\n\n9. **A Silent Voice (Koe no Katachi) (2016)** - Directed by Naoko Yamada, this film deals with themes of bullying, redemption, and friendship, focusing on a former bully seeking forgiveness from a deaf girl he tormented.\n\n10. **Weathering with You (2019)** - Another film from Makoto Shinkai, it tells the story of a boy who meets a girl with the ability to control the weather, exploring themes of climate change and love.\n\n11. **Perfect Blue (1997)** - Directed by Satoshi Kon, this psychological thriller delves into the dark side of fame and identity, following an idol-turned-actress who becomes the target of a stalker.\n\n12. **The Girl Who Leapt Through Time (2006)** - A blend of sci-fi and romance, this film follows a high school girl who gains the ability to time travel and the consequences that come with it.\n\nThese films represent just a fraction of the rich world of anime cinema. Each has its own unique style and story, making them worthwhile for both anime fans and newcomers alike.",
